DA VALENCA MASTER DOSSIER – LEONARDO DA VINCI MECHANICAL SYSTEMS

CORE THESIS
Leonardo da Vinci’s codices are not isolated sketches but fragments of a unified mechanical system.
They must be interpreted as layered, modular, and dynamic structures built around a central shaft and power transmission architecture.

CENTRAL SHAFT DOCTRINE
The central shaft acts as:
- geometric alignment axis across folios
- primary power transmission spine
- reference for all subsystems

All major components either:
- feed into the shaft
- are driven from the shaft
- regulate motion along the shaft

MECHANICAL CLASSES
1. Drive Systems
- hand cranks
- winding drums
- weighted inputs

2. Transmission Systems
- gear trains
- shafts
- rotating drums

3. Regulation Systems
- cam tracks
- travelling gears
- variable radius systems

4. Oscillation Systems
- pendulum-like motion
- cyclic engagement
- timed release mechanisms

5. Output Systems
- catapults
- lifting arms
- mechanical displays

6. Structural Systems
- frames
- supports
- bracing geometry

DRUM REGULATOR SYSTEM
A key discovery:
- rotating drum
- travelling gear
- cam-controlled lateral motion

Function:
- variable transmission
- speed modulation
- dynamic control

This is a governor system.

LAYERING SYSTEM
Folio interpretation progression:
- single page (incomplete)
- paired pages
- double pairs (4 layers)
- tri-stacked leaves
- extended systems across sequences

Seepage (bleed-through) is used as alignment data.

GEOMETRIC FRAMEWORK
- 2D drawings encode 3D systems
- perspective used intentionally
- alignment reveals depth (Z-axis)
- common use of proportional systems

SCALE DOCTRINE
Mechanisms appear at different scales:
- micro (precision)
- medium (functional)
- macro (military or large systems)

Example:
Catapult = scaled output module
Drum regulator = core control system

MODULAR ARCHITECTURE
The system is not one machine but a platform:
- interchangeable modules
- scalable designs
- shared mechanical logic

POWER TRAIN LOGIC
Energy flow:
Input → Central Shaft → Transmission → Regulation → Output

MOTION PRINCIPLE
All systems must be interpreted in motion:
- rotation
- oscillation
- guided displacement

STATIC interpretation is insufficient.

SYSTEM BOUNDARIES
Text-heavy verso pages often indicate:
- subsystem transitions
- conceptual breaks
- explanatory inserts

CODICES INCLUDED
- Madrid I & II
- Forster Notebooks
- Codex Atlanticus
- Codex Leicester

Each contributes partial system data.

FINAL SYNTHESIS
Leonardo’s work represents:
A unified mechanical language combining:
- geometry
- motion
- modular engineering
- scalable systems

It is a programmable mechanical architecture, not a collection of inventions.